## RQ1: Severity — Top 10 Counties {.smaller}

```{r}
#| fig-height: 5

top_counties |>
  mutate(label = paste0(county, ", ", state),
         label = fct_reorder(label, rate)) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = rate, y = label, fill = rate)) +
  geom_col(width = 0.7) +
  geom_text(aes(label = scales::percent(rate, 0.1)),
            hjust = -0.1, size = 3.8, color = "grey20", fontface = "bold") +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "#fdbb84", high = "#b30000", guide = "none") +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(),
                     expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.18))) +
  labs(title = "Top 10 Counties by Plumbing Deprivation Rate (2023)",
       subtitle = "Alaska dominates (7/10) — permafrost + remoteness · Southwest (3/10) — tribal lands",
       x = "Deprivation rate", y = NULL, caption = SOURCE_CAPTION) +
  theme(panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 11))
```

**Key Insights:** Alaska accounts for 7 of the 10 worst counties, with Kusilvak County exceeding 55% deprivation. The remaining three counties are in Arizona and New Mexico on tribal lands. Geographic concentration reflects permafrost/remoteness in Alaska and underinvestment in tribal infrastructure.

