## RQ3: Predictors — Population Effect {.smaller}

```{r}
#| fig-height: 5

ggplot(water_2023_clean, aes(x = log_pop, y = rate)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = rate), alpha = 0.45, size = 1.8) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ x,
              color = "#1a3f6f", fill = "#aec7e8",
              linewidth = 1.4, se = TRUE, alpha = 0.3) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "#fdbb84", high = "#b30000",
                       labels = scales::percent_format(),
                       name = "Rate") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 3:7,
                     labels = c("1K","10K","100K","1M","10M")) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(accuracy = 0.1)) +
  labs(title = "Larger Counties Have Significantly Lower Deprivation Rates",
       subtitle = paste0("OLS: rate = ", intercept_val, " + ", slope_val,
                         " × log₁₀(pop)   |   β₁ = ", slope_val, " (p < 0.001)   |   R² = ", r2_val),
       x = "County population (log₁₀ scale)", 
       y = "Deprivation rate",
       caption = SOURCE_CAPTION) +
  theme(legend.position = "right",
        legend.key.height = unit(1.2, "cm"))
```

**Key Insights:** Each tenfold increase in population is associated with a `r abs(round(slope_val*100, 2))` percentage-point decrease in deprivation rate (p < 0.001), confirming economies of scale. However, R² = `r r2_val` indicates population explains only 18% of variance — structural factors dominate.

