## RQ4: Trajectory — Year-over-Year Change {.smaller}

```{r}
#| fig-height: 5

water_change |>
  ggplot(aes(x = change, fill = direction)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 70, color = "white", alpha = 0.9, linewidth = 0.3) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = "solid",
             color = "grey30", linewidth = 1.2) +
  annotate("text", x = 0.01, y = Inf, 
           label = paste0("Improved: ", sum(water_change$direction=="Improved"), " counties"),
           hjust = 0, vjust = 2, color = "#2166ac", size = 4, fontface = "bold") +
  annotate("text", x = -0.01, y = Inf,
           label = paste0("Worsened: ", sum(water_change$direction=="Worsened"), " counties"),
           hjust = 1, vjust = 2, color = "#d6604d", size = 4, fontface = "bold") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Improved" = "#2166ac",
                               "Worsened" = "#d6604d"),
                    name = NULL) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(accuracy = 0.1),
                     breaks = seq(-0.1, 0.1, by = 0.02)) +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.12))) +
  labs(title = "Nearly Balanced Split: 1,487 Improved vs. 1,509 Worsened (2022→2023)",
       subtitle = paste0("Median Δ = ", scales::percent(median(water_change$change), 0.001), 
                         " · Extreme swings (> 5 pp) likely driven by sampling variance"),
       x = "Change in deprivation rate (percentage points)", 
       y = "Number of counties",
       caption = SOURCE_CAPTION) +
  theme(legend.position = "top",
        legend.text = element_text(size = 11))
```

**Key Insights:** Nearly balanced split between improved and worsened counties with median change ≈ 0, indicating aggregate stability. Extreme outliers (> 5 pp) more plausibly explained by sampling variance than genuine infrastructure change. Progress appears fragile without sustained investment.

