## Conclusions {.smaller}

::: columns
::: {.column width="50%"}
**Main Findings:**

1. Plumbing insecurity **geographically concentrated** in Alaska (7/10 top counties) and tribal Southwest (3/10)
2. **96% of counties** have near-universal access; only 34 counties (1.1%) exceed 5% deprivation
3. **Population matters** (β₁ = -0.0044, p < 0.001) but explains only 18% of variance
4. **Fragile progress**: year-over-year stability masks volatility in vulnerable counties
:::

::: {.column width="50%"}
**Implications:**

- **Targeted intervention** more efficient than universal programs
- Focus on 34 counties exceeding 5% threshold
- Address structural causes: tribal underinvestment, geographic isolation
- Sustained funding required for durable improvements

> *Water access is a proxy for structural inequality.*
:::
:::

